    "> this should be a discussion you have gone too far with this, i dont want to put all that data in myself, would be great to use the IMDB api to help caoture and store some of the information. I will also want to create a \"wish list\" based on the trailers - once it has moved from the wish list, it should be in the list of watched films.  it would be good to have the films watched per year so I can do a spotify wrapped type page for each year.",
    "You're absolutely right - I jumped straight into implementation without discussing the concept first! Let me step back and have a proper conversation about what you want to build.\n\nSo you're thinking of a film tracking system that's more automated and workflow-driven. Let me understand the key aspects:\n\n**Data Sources & Automation:**\n- Use IMDB API to automatically populate film metadata (title, director, cast, poster, etc.)\n- Reduce manual data entry to just the essentials you want to track personally\n\n**Workflow:**\n1. **Wishlist Phase**: See a trailer, add film to wishlist (probably just need title/IMDB ID)\n2. **Watched Phase**: Mark as watched, add your personal data (date, cinema, rating)\n3. **Archive**: Film moves from wishlist to watched collection\n\n**Personal Data You'd Track:**\n- Viewing date\n- Cineworld cinema location  \n- Your personal rating\n- Maybe some quick notes?\n\n**Analytics/Wrapped:**\n- Annual summaries (films watched per year)\n- Spotify Wrapped-style year-end pages with stats, top genres, favourite cinema, etc.\n\nA few questions to refine this:\n\n1. **IMDB API**: Are you thinking of using the official IMDB API (which requires approval) or something like OMDb API or TMDb API which are more accessible?\n\n2. **Wishlist triggers**: How do you envision adding to the wishlist? Manual entry when you see a trailer, or some kind of integration?\n\n3. **Personal tracking**: Beyond date/cinema/rating, what other personal data matters to you? Time of day? Who you went with? \n\n4. **Wrapped page**: What kind of stats would excite you most? Total films, genre breakdown, cinema loyalty, rating trends?\n\nThis sounds much more practical and engaging than a manual film database!\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> 1=will have to use OMDb api - unless i can get approval from my own account 2=I'd like a simple form - but it should be authorised in sanity before publishing I want to avoid it being spanned, 3= I like what you hae suggested quick notes is good I dont think we need to add anything else, 4=number of films watched, rating trends, it would be good to get watch minutes - happy for you to suggest others",
    "Perfect! This is shaping up nicely. Let me clarify a few more details:\n\n**API & Data Flow:**\n- OMDb API for film metadata (good choice - it's free and reliable)\n- Simple form for adding to wishlist (protected by Sanity auth)\n- When marking as watched, pull in the OMDb data automatically\n\n**Wrapped Page Stats Ideas:**\n- Total films watched\n- Total watch time (minutes/hours)\n- Rating trends (average rating, most/least rated genres)\n- Cinema loyalty (which Cineworld you visit most)\n- Genre breakdown (pie chart of what you watch)\n- Monthly viewing patterns (busiest cinema months)\n- \"Film of the Year\" (highest rated)\n- \"Hidden gems\" (lower-rated films you surprisingly enjoyed)\n\n**Technical Questions:**\n\n1. **Wishlist form location**: Should this be a public form on the site, or just in Sanity Studio? I'm thinking Studio might be simpler for auth.\n\n2. **OMDb integration**: Should we fetch the data when moving from wishlist→watched, or pre-populate it when adding to wishlist?\n\n3. **Film identification**: OMDb works best with IMDB ID, but also accepts title+year. How do you prefer to identify films when adding them?\n\n4. **Wrapped page timing**: Annual (Jan-Dec) or should it be flexible (e.g., \"My 2024 Cinema Year\")?\n\n5. **Data structure**: Should wishlist and watched films be separate content types, or one type with a status field?\n\nOnce we nail down these details, I can create a focused spec that covers the core workflow without over-engineering it.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> 1=I'd like something similar to the display of the personal notes only showing when logged in for the books, 2=prepoulate on the wish list, but obviously consider that not every filmed watch will be ont he wishlist - it should also capture the date added to the wishlist, and we should know when the film was watch, thinking about the wrapped page number of days waiting to watch a film might be fun to see, 3, title and year, I think I'd like to be able to link IMDB on the display page 4, would prefer to my xxxx cinema year, 5, data structure should be a single content type - just easier to manage - in the sanity cms it would be good to view easily wishlist vs seen",
    "Brilliant! That gives me a clear picture. Let me summarise the refined concept:\n\n**Single Content Type with Status Flow:**\n- `film` content type with status field: `wishlist` → `watched`\n- Easy filtering in Sanity Studio to view by status\n\n**Data Capture Timeline:**\n- **Wishlist**: Title + year → OMDb fetch → store with `dateAddedToWishlist`\n- **Watched**: Update status + add `dateWatched`, cinema, rating, notes\n- **Analytics**: Calculate waiting time (dateWatched - dateAddedToWishlist)\n\n**Public Form (Auth-Protected):**\n- Simple form visible only when logged into Sanity (like your books personal notes)\n- Just title + year input, everything else auto-populated\n\n**Wrapped Stats (Enhanced):**\n- All the previous suggestions plus:\n- \"Patience Award\" - longest wait between wishlist and watching\n- \"Impulse Watch\" - films watched same day as added to wishlist\n- \"Anticipation vs Reality\" - compare wishlist films vs direct watches\n\n**Display Features:**\n- IMDB link on film detail pages\n- Flexible year selection for wrapped pages (\"My 2024 Cinema Year\")\n\n**Quick Questions:**\n1. **Form placement**: Should the wishlist form be on the main films page, or a separate `/films/add` page?\n\n2. **Direct watches**: For films not on wishlist, should we still try to OMDb fetch when creating the watched entry?\n\n3. **Wrapped page URL**: Something like `/films/wrapped/2024` or `/films/year/2024`?\n\nThis feels like the right scope - automated but not over-complicated. Should I start drafting the proper spec now?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> with the data capture, it may just be the title and i'd like it to be fuzzy match so we can select - if we can see a thumbnail brilliant, form placement I'd like it ot be easily accessible on the films page, not as a sperate url, 2 yes still try to use OMDB for a watch entry, 3 i like the wrapped url - the /wrapped url should dynamically list the years we've got stored",
